{"parse":{"title":"Pellegrina","pageid":36747392,"revid":858149900,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For the wine grape that is also known as Pellegrina, see <a href=\"/wiki/Sauvignon_blanc\" title=\"Sauvignon blanc\">Sauvignon blanc</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Carmelo_Canzonieri.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/Carmelo_Canzonieri.jpg/220px-Carmelo_Canzonieri.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"266\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/39/Carmelo_Canzonieri.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"280\" data-file-height=\"339\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Carmelo_Canzonieri.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Catholic bishop wearing an <a href=\"/wiki/Amaranth_(color)\" title=\"Amaranth (color)\">amaranth red</a>-trimmed black <a href=\"/wiki/Cassock\" title=\"Cassock\">cassock</a> and pellegrina</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>pellegrina</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Cape\" title=\"Cape\">cape</a>-like item of clerical dress worn by some <a href=\"/wiki/Catholic_Church\" title=\"Catholic Church\">Catholic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Clergy\" title=\"Clergy\">ecclesiastics</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Description\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Description</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Use\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Use</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Origin_of_the_name\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Origin of the name</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pellegrina&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Similar to the <a href=\"/wiki/Mozzetta\" title=\"Mozzetta\">mozzetta</a> but open in front, the pellegrina is a short shoulder cape reaching to the elbow. It is made of black or white material trimmed and lined with <a href=\"/wiki/Amaranth_(color)\" title=\"Amaranth (color)\">amaranth red</a> (for bishops) or <a href=\"/wiki/Scarlet_(color)\" title=\"Scarlet (color)\">scarlet red</a> (for <a href=\"/wiki/Cardinalate\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cardinalate\">cardinals</a>). The <a href=\"/wiki/Pope\" title=\"Pope\">pope</a>'s pellegrina is entirely white.  In some countries, priests wear a pellegrina of the same colour as their plain black cassock.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Use\">Use</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pellegrina&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Use\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg/250px-Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"188\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg/375px-Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg/500px-Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2048\" data-file-height=\"1536\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Papa_Benedetto_XVI_-_21_settembre_2005.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Pope_Benedict_XVI\" title=\"Pope Benedict XVI\">Pope Benedict XVI</a> wearing a white pellegrina</div></div></div>\n<p>The general rule of the Roman Catholic Church is that the pellegrina may be worn with the <a href=\"/wiki/Cassock\" title=\"Cassock\">cassock</a> by cardinals and bishops.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Instruction_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Instruction-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1850, the year in which <a href=\"/wiki/Pope_Pius_IX\" title=\"Pope Pius IX\">Pope Pius IX</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Universalis_Ecclesiae\" title=\"Universalis Ecclesiae\">restored the Catholic hierarchy</a> in England and Wales, he was understood to grant to all priests there the privilege of wearing a replica in black of his own white cassock with pellegrina.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Since then, the wearing of the pellegrina with the cassock has been a sign of a Catholic priest in England and Wales, Scotland, Ireland, Australia, and New Zealand.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pallottines1.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Pallottines1.jpg/220px-Pallottines1.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"147\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Pallottines1.jpg/330px-Pallottines1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Pallottines1.jpg/440px-Pallottines1.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3456\" data-file-height=\"2304\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pallottines1.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Polish Palottine Fathers wearing cassocks with pellegrinas</div></div></div>\n<p>In his 1909 book, <i>Costume of Prelates of the Catholic Church</i>, John Abel Felix Prosper Nainfa <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.google.com/search?tbm=bks&amp;tbo=1&amp;q=nainfa+%22adopting+the+English+word+simar%22&amp;btnG=Search+Books\">proposed</a> the use of the English word \"<a href=\"/wiki/Simar\" title=\"Simar\">simar</a>\", instead of the word \"cassock\", for the garment with shoulder cape, which he treated as distinct from the cassock proper. Others too have made the same distinction between the \"simar\" (with pellegrina) and the \"cassock\" (without), but many scholars disagree with Nainfa's distinction.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McNamara_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McNamara-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> More particularly, the documents of the <a href=\"/wiki/Holy_See\" title=\"Holy See\">Holy See</a> make no such distinction, using the term \"cassock\" or \"vestis talaris\" whether a pellegrina is attached or is not. Thus the 1969 Instruction states that, for cardinals and bishops, \"the elbow-length cape, trimmed in the same manner as this <i>cassock</i>, may be worn over it\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Instruction_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Instruction-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \"Cassock\", rather than \"simar\" is the term that is usually applied to the dress of Popes and other Catholic ecclesiastics. The Instruction also gives no support to Nainfa's claim that the cassock with shoulder cape should not be worn in church services, which would be of difficult application, since the cassock with pellegrina is generally made as a single garment, with a non-detachable pellegrina.\n</p><p>When Pope Benedict XVI resigned in 2013, he decided that he would continue to wear a white cassock but without pellegrina.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<center>\n<table class=\"wikitable\">\n\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><div class=\"center\"><div class=\"floatnone\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pellegrina_(Pope).svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Pellegrina (Pope).svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Pellegrina_%28Pope%29.svg/160px-Pellegrina_%28Pope%29.svg.png\" width=\"160\" height=\"184\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Pellegrina_%28Pope%29.svg/240px-Pellegrina_%28Pope%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Pellegrina_%28Pope%29.svg/320px-Pellegrina_%28Pope%29.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"448\" data-file-height=\"514\" /></a></div></div>\n</td>\n<td><div class=\"center\"><div class=\"floatnone\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pellegrina_(Cardinal).svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Pellegrina (Cardinal).svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Pellegrina_%28Cardinal%29.svg/160px-Pellegrina_%28Cardinal%29.svg.png\" width=\"160\" height=\"184\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Pellegrina_%28Cardinal%29.svg/240px-Pellegrina_%28Cardinal%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Pellegrina_%28Cardinal%29.svg/320px-Pellegrina_%28Cardinal%29.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"448\" data-file-height=\"514\" /></a></div></div>\n</td>\n<td><div class=\"center\"><div class=\"floatnone\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pellegrina_(Bishop).svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Pellegrina (Bishop).svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Pellegrina_%28Bishop%29.svg/160px-Pellegrina_%28Bishop%29.svg.png\" width=\"160\" height=\"184\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Pellegrina_%28Bishop%29.svg/240px-Pellegrina_%28Bishop%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Pellegrina_%28Bishop%29.svg/320px-Pellegrina_%28Bishop%29.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"448\" data-file-height=\"514\" /></a></div></div>\n</td>\n<td><div class=\"center\"><div class=\"floatnone\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pellegrina_(Priest).svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Pellegrina (Priest).svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Pellegrina_%28Priest%29.svg/160px-Pellegrina_%28Priest%29.svg.png\" width=\"160\" height=\"184\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Pellegrina_%28Priest%29.svg/240px-Pellegrina_%28Priest%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Pellegrina_%28Priest%29.svg/320px-Pellegrina_%28Priest%29.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"448\" data-file-height=\"514\" /></a></div></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Pope\n</td>\n<td>Cardinal\n</td>\n<td>Bishop\n</td>\n<td>Priest\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n</center>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origin_of_the_name\">Origin of the name</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pellegrina&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Origin of the name\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The pellegrina owes its name to its similarity to a more ample shoulder cape of cloth or leather that was traditionally worn by pilgrims (<i>pellegrini</i> in <a href=\"/wiki/Italian_language\" title=\"Italian language\">Italian</a>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-McNamara_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McNamara-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pellegrina&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Instruction-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Instruction_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Instruction_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www2.fiu.edu/~mirandas/instruction69.htm\">Instruction <i>Ut sive sollicite</i> on the Dress, Titles and Coats-of-Arms of Cardinals, Bishops and Lesser Prelates, 28 March 1969, 2 and 14</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.catholic-history.org.uk/nwchs/plumb/glossary.html\">Catholic History: England &amp; Wales 1550\u20131850, s.v. \"Clerical dress\"</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20131021024031/http://www.catholic-history.org.uk/nwchs/plumb/glossary.html\">Archived</a> 2013-10-21 at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-McNamara-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-McNamara_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McNamara_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.ewtn.com/library/liturgy/zlitur444.htm\">Edward McNamara, \"Birettas and Academic Hats at Mass\"</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.quibrescia.it/cms/2013/02/26/dopo-laddio-benedetto-xvi-sara-papa-emerito/?rnd=1575729654\">\"Dopo l'addio Benedetto XVI sar\u00e0 'Papa emerito'\"</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.catholicnews.com/services/englishnews/2013/pope-benedict-to-be-pope-emeritus-or-roman-pontiff-emeritus.cfm\">Cindy Wooden, \"Pope Benedict to be 'Pope emeritus' or 'Roman pontiff emeritus'\", <i>Catholic News Service</i></a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1266\nCached time: 20180909133012\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.076 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.107 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 174/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 998/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 74/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2896/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.016/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 801 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   58.471      1 -total\n 48.67%   28.459      1 Template:For\n 41.40%   24.209      1 Template:Reflist\n 20.77%   12.147      1 Template:Webarchive\n  3.02%    1.765      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:36747392-0!canonical and timestamp 20180909133012 and revision id 858149900\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"de","url":"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pellegrina","langname":"German","autonym":"Deutsch","*":"Pellegrina"},{"lang":"es","url":"https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esclavina","langname":"Spanish","autonym":"espa\u00f1ol","*":"Esclavina"},{"lang":"it","url":"https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pellegrina","langname":"Italian","autonym":"italiano","*":